    term: "Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)",
    slug: "rag",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Large language models have a fundamental limitation. They can only work with information they learned during their original training, which usually has a cutoff date. Ask ChatGPT about events from last week, and it genuinely does not know what happened. This creates a problem for businesses and researchers who need AI systems that stay current with new information.  Retrieval-Augmented Generation solves this problem by teaching AI models to look things up before answering questions. Think of it like giving an AI assistant access to a constantly updated library. When you ask a question, the system performs two steps in sequence. First, it searches through its knowledge base to find relevant documents, articles, or data. Second, it reads those materials and crafts an answer based on what it discovered.  Consider a customer service scenario. A traditional AI model might struggle to answer questions about a product feature that launched yesterday because that information was not in its training data. With RAG, the system searches the company's updated documentation, finds the relevant details about the new feature, and uses that fresh information to provide an accurate response.  This approach brings several major benefits. AI responses become more factual because the system works with real source material instead of relying purely on memory. Hallucinations decrease significantly when models have concrete information to reference. Companies can keep their AI systems current by simply updating their knowledge databases without the massive expense of retraining entire models.  The search component determines whether RAG succeeds or fails. When the system retrieves the right documents, the AI produces helpful, accurate answers. When it pulls irrelevant or outdated materials, responses become confused or wrong. Building effective search requires careful attention to how information gets organized, indexed, and matched to user queries.  RAG powers most enterprise AI applications today. Customer support chatbots use it to access current product manuals and troubleshooting guides. Internal search tools help employees find specific policies or procedures within company documents. Research assistants pull from academic databases to support scholarly work. Legal AI systems reference case law and regulatory updates.  The knowledge base can contain almost any type of information. Companies often include product documentation, frequently asked questions, internal wikis, and training materials. News organizations might feed in recent articles. Research institutions could provide access to academic papers and datasets.  Setting up RAG requires thoughtful planning. Organizations must decide what information to include, how to structure it for effective searching, and how frequently to update it. The quality of results depends heavily on the quality of the underlying knowledge base.  This technology represents a practical solution to keeping AI systems useful in rapidly changing environments. Rather than accepting outdated AI responses, RAG enables systems that grow smarter as new information becomes available. For businesses seeking reliable AI assistance, this capability often makes the difference between a helpful tool and an expensive frustration.",
