    term: "Token",
    slug: "token",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "When you type a message to an AI like ChatGPT, the computer doesn't actually read your words the way humans do. Instead, it breaks your text down into tiny pieces called tokens. These pieces help the AI understand and process what you're saying.  Tokens work differently than you might expect. They're not quite the same as words. Simple, common words like \"the,\" \"and,\" or \"cat\" usually become one token each. But longer words or unusual words get chopped up into smaller chunks. For example, the word \"understand\" might become two tokens like \"under\" and \"stand.\" A complex word like \"extraordinary\" could split into three or four pieces.  The AI system looks at patterns in these token pieces to figure out meaning and generate responses. Think of it like a jigsaw puzzle where each token is a piece that helps complete the bigger picture of understanding language.  Here's a helpful rule of thumb for English text. One token equals roughly three-quarters of a regular word. So if you have 100 tokens, that's about 75 actual words. A paragraph of 200 words would use approximately 265 tokens. This measurement becomes important when you start working with AI systems.  Every AI model has something called a context window. This window determines how many tokens the AI can remember and work with in a single conversation. Imagine the AI's memory as a container that can only hold a certain number of token pieces at once. When the container fills up, older tokens get pushed out to make room for new ones.  Different AI models have dramatically different container sizes. GPT-4 can handle around 128,000 tokens at once. That's enough space for roughly 96,000 words, which equals a short novel or a very long research paper. Smaller AI models might only manage 4,000 tokens, giving you space for about 3,000 words or just a few pages of text.  This limitation affects how you can use AI. If you want to ask questions about a long document, you need an AI with a large enough context window to fit the entire document plus your questions and the AI's responses. Running out of token space means the AI forgets earlier parts of your conversation.  Money matters here too. When you use AI services through their programming interfaces, you typically pay based on how many tokens you use. Shorter messages cost less than longer ones. A brief question might use 50 tokens and cost fractions of a penny, while a detailed analysis of a long document could use thousands of tokens and cost several dollars.  Different AI companies split text into tokens using their own methods. The same sentence might create 15 tokens in one system but 18 tokens in another. This difference affects both cost and how much text fits in the AI's memory window.  Understanding tokens helps you use AI more effectively and economically. You can write more concise prompts to save money and fit more information into the AI's memory space.",
