    term: "Quantization",
    slug: "quantization",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Quantization makes artificial intelligence models smaller and more efficient so they can run on everyday computers. Think of it like compressing a high-resolution photo to make it take up less storage space while keeping it recognizable.  When engineers build AI models, they store the model's knowledge as millions or billions of numbers called weights. These numbers represent everything the AI has learned during training. Normally, each weight gets stored with extreme precision using 32 bits of data. This creates incredibly detailed information but requires enormous amounts of computer memory and processing power.  Quantization reduces the precision of these numbers without destroying the AI's ability to function. Instead of using 32 bits per weight, quantization might use 8 bits, 4 bits, or even fewer. Picture the difference between measuring something with a ruler marked in millimeters versus one marked only in centimeters. You lose some detail, but for most purposes, the measurement still works perfectly well.  The space savings can be dramatic. A large language model that normally takes 140 gigabytes of storage might shrink to just 40 gigabytes when quantized to 4-bit precision. This transforms a model that requires expensive server equipment into one that fits comfortably on a gaming computer or even a laptop.  The process works because AI models contain significant redundancy. Many weights contribute similar information, so reducing their precision often has minimal impact on performance. Modern quantization techniques have become sophisticated enough to identify which weights can safely lose precision and which need to maintain their full detail.  Several tools make quantization accessible to regular users. GGUF, GPTQ, and AWQ are popular quantization formats that different software can understand. Projects like llama.cpp and Ollama specialize in running quantized models on personal computers. These tools handle the complex mathematics behind the scenes, letting users simply download and run powerful AI models locally.  This technology has democratized access to advanced AI capabilities. Before quantization became widespread, running large language models required expensive cloud services or specialized hardware costing thousands of dollars. Now, someone with a decent laptop can run models that rival commercial AI services, completely offline and without ongoing costs.  The quality trade-offs are surprisingly small. While some precision gets lost during quantization, carefully quantized models often perform nearly as well as their full-precision counterparts on practical tasks. For most users, the difference is unnoticeable, while the benefits of local operation are substantial.  Quantization represents a crucial bridge between cutting-edge AI research and practical applications. It enables privacy-conscious users to keep their data local, reduces dependence on internet connections, eliminates recurring subscription fees, and makes AI experimentation accessible to students, researchers, and hobbyists worldwide.  Without quantization, powerful AI would remain locked behind expensive cloud services controlled by major technology companies. Instead, this technique has sparked a vibrant ecosystem of local AI applications, putting advanced artificial intelligence directly into the hands of everyday users.",
    relatedTerms: ["llm", "inference", "model-distillation"]
