    term: "Flash Loan",
    slug: "flash-loan",
    category: "Web3",
    definition: "Flash loans represent one of the most unusual financial tools in cryptocurrency. These loans allow anyone to borrow massive amounts of digital money without putting up any collateral or security deposit. The catch is that you must repay the entire loan within a single blockchain transaction, which typically takes just seconds to complete.  Traditional loans require collateral like your house or car as security. If you cannot repay, the lender keeps your collateral. Flash loans work differently because of how blockchain transactions function. Every transaction either succeeds completely or fails completely. There is no middle ground. If any part of a transaction fails, the entire transaction reverses as if it never happened.  This creates a unique situation. When you take a flash loan, you must include instructions for both borrowing the money and repaying it in the same transaction. If your repayment fails for any reason, the blockchain automatically cancels the entire transaction, including the original loan. The lender never actually loses money because either they get paid back with fees, or the loan never technically happens.  Smart traders use flash loans for arbitrage opportunities. Suppose Bitcoin trades for $30,000 on Exchange A but $30,200 on Exchange B. A trader can borrow $300,000 through a flash loan, buy 10 Bitcoins on Exchange A, immediately sell them on Exchange B for $302,000, repay the $300,000 loan plus fees, and keep the profit. This entire sequence happens in one transaction without the trader risking their own money.  Flash loans also help people manage their existing cryptocurrency investments. Someone with money locked in a lending protocol might want to move it to a better opportunity. Normally, they would need to withdraw their funds, losing interest during the transfer process. With flash loans, they can borrow money to invest in the new opportunity immediately, then use those returns to pay off their original position and repay the flash loan.  Unfortunately, flash loans have become powerful tools for attacking cryptocurrency protocols. Hackers exploit a common weakness where protocols rely on external price information. An attacker might borrow millions through a flash loan, use that money to manipulate prices on a smaller exchange, then trick a lending protocol into thinking an asset is worth more than its true value. They can borrow against this inflated collateral, repay the original flash loan, and escape with stolen funds.  These attacks have cost the cryptocurrency industry hundreds of millions of dollars. The speed and scale possible with flash loans turn minor vulnerabilities into major disasters. A bug that might allow someone to steal a few thousand dollars becomes catastrophic when an attacker can temporarily control millions.  Flash loans demonstrate both the innovation and risks in decentralized finance. They enable previously impossible trading strategies and financial operations. However, they also amplify the impact of security vulnerabilities. As the technology matures, protocols are developing better defenses against flash loan attacks while preserving the legitimate benefits these tools provide.",
