    term: "Few-Shot Prompting",
    slug: "few-shot-prompting",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "When you want an artificial intelligence to perform a specific task, simply telling it what to do often isn't enough. The AI might misunderstand your request or produce results in the wrong format. Few-shot prompting solves this problem by showing the AI a handful of examples before asking it to complete your actual task.  Picture teaching a friend how to write product descriptions for your online store. Instead of just saying \"write product descriptions,\" you would show them several examples of good descriptions you've already written. They would see the style, length, and information you include. Then when you ask them to write a description for a new product, they can follow the same pattern.  Few-shot prompting works the same way with AI. You provide two to five examples that demonstrate exactly what you want, then give the AI your real request. The AI analyzes the patterns in your examples and applies the same approach to your new input.  Consider asking an AI to classify customer feedback as positive, negative, or neutral. Without examples, the AI might struggle with borderline cases or use inconsistent criteria. With few-shot prompting, you would first show the AI several feedback messages paired with their correct classifications. For instance, you might show that \"The product arrived quickly and works perfectly\" gets labeled as positive, while \"Shipping was delayed but the item is okay\" gets labeled as neutral. After seeing these patterns, the AI can classify new feedback much more accurately.  The quality of your examples determines the success of few-shot prompting. Good examples should represent different aspects of your task. If you're teaching the AI to write email subject lines, include examples for different types of emails like newsletters, promotions, and announcements. Make sure your examples use the exact format you want because the AI will copy that structure precisely.  Diversity in examples prevents the AI from fixating on irrelevant details. If all your examples happen to mention the color blue, the AI might think color is always important even when it's not. The order of examples can also influence results since some AI models pay extra attention to the most recent example you provide.  Few-shot prompting has practical limitations. Complex tasks might require more examples than you can fit in a single prompt. Some AI systems have limits on how much text they can process at once. Additionally, tasks requiring genuine reasoning or creativity might not improve much from examples alone.  Despite these constraints, few-shot prompting dramatically improves AI performance for most everyday tasks. Whether you need the AI to format data, answer questions in a specific style, or generate content following particular guidelines, providing three to five well-chosen examples typically produces much better results than giving no examples at all.  The technique works because it reduces ambiguity and gives the AI concrete patterns to follow. Instead of guessing what you want, the AI can reference your examples to understand both the task requirements and your preferred output style.",
