    term: "Prompt Tuning",
    slug: "prompt-tuning",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Large language models like ChatGPT work by processing text through mathematical representations. When you type a sentence, the model converts each word into numbers it can understand. Prompt tuning takes advantage of this process by adding special mathematical instructions that exist only as numbers, not as readable words.  Think of a traditional prompt as giving someone written instructions in English. You might write \"Please summarize this article in a friendly tone.\" The person reads your words and follows them. Prompt tuning works differently. Instead of using readable words, it learns to create mathematical signals that tell the model what to do. These signals are called soft prompts because they're flexible and learnable, unlike the hard prompts we write with actual words.  When researchers use prompt tuning, they start with a pre-trained model that stays completely frozen. Nothing about the original model changes. Instead, they train a small set of mathematical vectors that get attached to the beginning of whatever input you provide. These vectors might represent concepts like \"be helpful\" or \"focus on technical details,\" but they exist purely as numbers in the model's mathematical space.  The training process teaches these soft prompts to guide the model toward better performance on specific tasks. If you want the model to become better at medical question answering, the soft prompt learns mathematical patterns that nudge the model in that direction. The original model never changes, but these prepended instructions alter how it interprets and responds to inputs.  Prompt tuning requires remarkably few resources compared to other training methods. While a large language model might have billions of parameters, a soft prompt typically uses only 20 to 100 learned vectors. This represents less than one-tenth of one percent of the total model size. You can train these prompts quickly and store them efficiently.  The effectiveness of prompt tuning scales with model size. Smaller models struggle to follow these mathematical instructions effectively. However, when Google researchers tested prompt tuning on an 11-billion parameter model, it performed just as well as completely retraining the entire model. This suggests that larger models become better at interpreting these numerical guidance signals.  Prompt tuning works best for well-defined, consistent tasks. If you need a model to always respond in a particular style or focus on specific types of information, soft prompts can learn these patterns effectively. However, complex tasks that require fundamental changes to how the model processes information might need more intensive training approaches.  During actual use, the process remains invisible to users. The soft prompt automatically attaches to whatever input you provide, guides the model's processing, and produces the desired output. You never see or interact with the mathematical vectors directly.  This technique offers a practical middle ground between using models as-is and the expensive process of full retraining. Organizations can adapt powerful models to their specific needs without the computational costs and technical complexity of training entire models from scratch.",
