    definition: "Vision Transformer represents a breakthrough approach to teaching computers how to see and understand images. Traditional computer vision systems relied on specialized neural networks called convolutional neural networks, which were specifically designed to process visual information. Vision Transformer took a completely different path by borrowing the transformer architecture that had proven incredibly successful for language processing tasks.  The core innovation lies in how Vision Transformer treats images. Instead of processing an image as a whole visual scene, it cuts the image into small, square pieces called patches. Think of taking a photograph and slicing it into a grid of tiny squares, like cutting a pizza into uniform pieces. Each patch typically measures 16 pixels by 16 pixels. The system then flattens each patch into a long list of numbers that represents the colors and brightness values in that small section.  These flattened patches become the building blocks for the transformer to work with. Just as a language transformer processes words in a sentence, Vision Transformer processes these image patches as individual elements in a sequence. The system adds special position markers to each patch so it remembers where each piece originally belonged in the image.  The transformer then applies its signature attention mechanism to these patches. This attention system allows each patch to \"look at\" and gather information from every other patch in the image, regardless of how far apart they were in the original picture. A patch from the top-left corner can directly interact with a patch from the bottom-right corner, something that traditional vision systems handled less efficiently.  What makes this approach remarkable is that transformers have no built-in understanding of spatial relationships or visual patterns. They do not automatically know that nearby pixels usually relate to each other, or that edges and shapes matter for understanding images. Despite lacking these visual assumptions, Vision Transformer can match and sometimes exceed the performance of specialized vision networks.  The key requirement is scale. Vision Transformer needs massive amounts of training data to work effectively. When trained on smaller datasets, traditional convolutional networks typically perform better. However, when given access to millions or billions of images during training, Vision Transformer often surpasses older approaches. This pattern mirrors what researchers observed with language models, where bigger models trained on more text generally perform better.  Vision Transformer opened new possibilities for artificial intelligence systems. Since the same transformer architecture can handle both text and images, researchers can now build unified models that understand multiple types of information. This breakthrough enabled the creation of systems that can simultaneously process and understand both written descriptions and visual content.  The success of Vision Transformer spawned numerous variations and improvements. Some versions focus on training efficiency, others incorporate hierarchical processing similar to traditional vision networks, and some use techniques borrowed from language model training like masked prediction tasks.  This approach fundamentally changed how researchers think about computer vision, proving that general-purpose architectures can excel at specialized tasks when given sufficient data and computational resources.",
