    term: "Optical Character Recognition",
    slug: "ocr",
    category: "AI",
    definition: "Optical Character Recognition, commonly called OCR, transforms pictures of text into digital words that computers can understand and work with. When you take a photo of a handwritten note or scan an old document, the computer initially sees only a collection of dots and lines. OCR technology analyzes these visual patterns and converts them into actual text you can edit, search through, and copy.  Picture trying to read a foreign alphabet for the first time. You would look at each symbol, compare it to examples you know, and gradually piece together the meaning. OCR works similarly but much faster. The software examines each character in an image, compares it against thousands of known letter and number patterns, then makes educated guesses about what each symbol represents.  Early OCR systems relied on rigid rules and templates. They could only handle specific fonts printed clearly on clean paper. These systems would fail completely if text was slightly rotated, smudged, or written in an unexpected style. Modern OCR has become far more sophisticated by incorporating artificial intelligence and machine learning.  Today's OCR systems use neural networks that learn from millions of text examples. These networks can handle cursive handwriting, faded documents, photographs taken at odd angles, and text embedded in complex backgrounds. The technology has become so advanced that it can read street signs in smartphone photos, digitize centuries-old manuscripts, and process receipts with crumpled surfaces.  The recognition process happens in several stages. First, the system locates where text appears in an image, separating it from backgrounds, pictures, or decorative elements. Next, it identifies individual characters or words within those text regions. Finally, it applies language understanding to correct obvious mistakes and improve accuracy.  Different types of OCR tackle different challenges. Document OCR focuses on books, papers, and forms, handling multiple columns, tables, and various formatting styles. Scene text OCR works with text found in natural environments like storefronts, billboards, and product packaging. Handwriting recognition represents the most difficult category because every person writes differently.  Modern OCR applications have transformed many industries. Banks use it to process checks automatically. Libraries digitize rare books to preserve them electronically. Mobile apps translate foreign signs instantly by reading them through your camera. Businesses convert paper invoices into searchable digital files. Accessibility tools read printed text aloud for visually impaired users.  The accuracy of OCR depends on image quality, text clarity, and language complexity. Clean, high-contrast text achieves near-perfect recognition rates. Handwritten notes or damaged documents require more sophisticated processing and may still contain errors.  As OCR technology continues advancing, it increasingly handles previously impossible tasks. Recent systems can read text printed on curved surfaces, process multiple languages simultaneously, and maintain original formatting when converting documents. This progress makes digital information more accessible and reduces the time humans spend manually entering data from physical sources.",
