    slug: "liquid-restaking",
    category: "Web3",
    definition: "Liquid restaking represents one of the most ambitious experiments in cryptocurrency finance, allowing investors to earn rewards from multiple blockchain networks using the same pool of money. To understand how this works, you need to grasp the building blocks that make it possible.  When you own Ethereum tokens, you can participate in \"staking\" by locking your tokens to help secure the Ethereum network. Think of this like putting money in a savings account that pays interest, except your deposit also helps keep the blockchain running safely. Traditional staking requires you to lock up your tokens, making them unavailable for other uses.  Liquid staking solved this limitation by giving you a receipt token when you stake. If you stake 10 ETH, you receive 10 stETH tokens that represent your staked position. These receipt tokens can be traded or used in other financial applications while your original ETH continues earning staking rewards.  Restaking takes this concept further. Protocols like EigenLayer allow you to use your already-staked ETH to secure additional blockchain networks beyond Ethereum. These could be bridge networks that connect different blockchains, oracle services that provide real-world data to smart contracts, or specialized transaction processing systems. Each additional network you help secure pays you extra rewards, but also exposes you to additional risks called \"slashing conditions.\"  Slashing means losing part of your staked tokens as punishment for malicious behavior or technical failures. When you restake across multiple networks, you face slashing risks from each one. If any network you support experiences problems, you could lose money even if you did nothing wrong.  Liquid restaking automates this complex process through specialized protocols. You deposit your ETH into a liquid restaking protocol, which handles the technical details of spreading your stake across multiple networks. In return, you receive liquid restaking tokens that can be freely traded or used in other applications.  The efficiency gains are remarkable. Your original ETH simultaneously earns rewards from securing Ethereum, generates additional income from supporting other networks, and can serve as collateral for loans or trading in decentralized finance applications. One dollar of ETH might effectively work as three dollars of capital.  However, this efficiency comes with significant risks. If one of the smaller networks you support experiences a slashing event, the consequences can ripple through the entire system. Imagine a chain reaction where problems in a minor network force the liquidation of loans secured by liquid restaking tokens, which then affects other interconnected financial products.  Popular liquid restaking protocols include Ether.fi and Puffer, which manage portfolios of different networks and distribute user stakes accordingly. These platforms promise higher yields by optimizing which networks to support and managing the associated risks.  Liquid restaking represents the frontier of capital efficiency in cryptocurrency, where the same money works multiple jobs simultaneously. While this creates opportunities for enhanced returns, it also concentrates risks in ways that could amplify problems across the broader ecosystem. Understanding both the potential rewards and systemic dangers helps investors make informed decisions about participating in these experimental financial systems.",
    relatedTerms: ["liquid-staking", "defi", "validator"]
